               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18560514-507-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-507-18560514 t18560514-507-offence-1 t18560514-507-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>507. <persName id="def1-507-18560514" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-507-18560514" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-507-18560514" type="age" value="21"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-507-18560514" type="surname" value="GRIFFITHS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-507-18560514" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN GRIFFITHS</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18560514-507-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18560514-507-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18560514-507-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="burglary"></interp>, burglariously breaking and entering the dwell<lb></lb>ing house of <persName id="t18560514-name-301" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-301" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-301" type="surname" value="TOMLINSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-301" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-301" type="occupation" value="fishmonger"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18560514-507-offence-1 t18560514-name-301"></join>Thomas Tomlinson</persName>, and stealing a looking glass, work box, snuff box, and brooch, value 13<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; his property.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-302" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-302" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-302" type="surname" value="CARTY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-302" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN CARTY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a labourer, and live in the house of Mr. Tomlinson, a fishmonger, No. 71, Lower Thames-street Between 3 and 4 o'clock on. Sunday morning, 20th April, I had occasion to come down stairs to the water closet, and found a man bursting out through the window on to a bench underneath, it—the house stands up a passage, and the window faces the street—I pursued the man, calling "Stop thief!"—I did not see his face, only his back, but I never lost sight of him till I left the constable in pursuit of him and then both the man and the constable got out of my sight—to the best of my belief, the prisoner is the man; he is the man that was brought back—I could not swear to him, because I did not see his face, but he resembles the man in size and dress—I after<lb></lb>wards examined the window, it was open, the lower part slides up, two panes of glass were broken, and two nails which fastened down the sash were removed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> What distance were you from where the man jumped out</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140251"></xptr>
               <p>of the window? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About one pace—he came out on his hands and knees, which prevented my fleeing his face, and ran down the passage, and I after him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-303" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-303" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-303" type="surname" value="TOMKINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-303" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH TOMKINS</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">City policeman</hi>, 587). A little before 4 o'clock on Sun<lb></lb>day morning, 20th April, I was in Lower Thames-street—I heard the breaking of glass—I went to No. 71, I waited two or three minutes, and saw the prisoner come out of the court—I pursued him along Thames-street—I lost sight of him for about half a minute on Tower-hill, I sprang my rattle, and after I turned the corner of the rails round the Tower ditch, I saw him ia the hands of <hi rend="italic">H</hi> 75—he was not half a minute out of my sight—I had seen him during the night, about 1 o'clock, in company with another man, standing very near the court; I watched them away, and they went towards London-bridge—I afterwards saw him again, about 3 o'clock, coming out of Harp-lane into Thames-street, that is about fifty yards from the prosecutor's premises.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Whereabouts were you standing when you say I came I down the court? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I was about two yards from the court when you ran out—you ran faster than me, or I should have laid hold of you.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-304" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-304" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-304" type="surname" value="STARTIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-304" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM STARTIN</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">policeman, H</hi> 75). On Sunday morning, 20th April, About a quarter to 4 o'clock, I was in Trinity-square, Tower-hill, and heard the springing of a rattle—I turned, and saw the prisoner running across Tower-hill, towards the Mint, in a direction from Lower Thames-street—I stopped him, he was out of breath—Tomkins came up in about half a minute, and recognised him—I searched him—before I did so, he gave me 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. and a lucifer match when I asked what he had got about him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-305" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-305" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-305" type="surname" value="BUTTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-305" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES BUTTON</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">City policemen</hi>, 569). A little before 4 o'clock on Sunday morning I was on duty in Lower Thames-street, and heard a cry of "Stop thief!"—I went to No. 71, Lower Thames-street, and saw Carty—I picked up this looking glass on a bench under the window—two panes of the lower sash of that window were broken, near the fastening—I found a work box and a snuff box outside—I called Mrs. Tomlinson and her son up, and then examined the room—I found one of the drawers open, and some things that were taken from it, on the window ledge—I found this screw-driver outside in the street, and some lucifer matches about fifty yards from the passage in Thames-street, nearer to Tower-hill—this snuff box, brooch, and pair of tweezers were picked up in Thames-street—I also found a piece of candle in the court—the matches correspond with the one which the prisoner had on him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-306" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-306" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-306" type="surname" value="TOMLINSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-306" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS TOMLINSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a fishmonger, at No. 71, Lower Thames-street, in the parish of St. Dunstan in the East I was not at home on the night in question, my son and my wife were in the house—these articles (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) are mine—I lost a silk handkerchief altogether, from a drawer that was not locked.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-307" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-307" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-307" type="surname" value="TOMLIKSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-307" type="given" value="THOMAS CHARLES"></interp>THOMAS CHARLES TOMLIKSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the son of the last witness. I went to bed at a quarter to 11 o'clock on 19th April—before doing so I examined the window of the ground floor room—it was fastened with two nails, quite secure—I saw some of these things on the sideboard, in front of the window, and some were in the drawers—the handkerchief that is lost was in a drawer—I saw it there about 8 o'clock on Saturday evening, and also a sixpence in the work box—the street door was not fastened—I locked the room door, and had the key—I found it still locked in the morning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-308" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-308" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-308" type="surname" value="BUTTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-308" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES BUTTON</persName>
                  </hi>. <hi rend="italic">re-excmined.</hi> There was no sixpence in the box when I found it.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140252"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> On the night of the robbery I went to Drury-lane Theatre, and fell in company with a young man, a sailor, who said he was steward on board a ship; we went to a public house, and met a friend of his, and went to his house, where we remained till about 3 o'clock in the morning; we then came away, and, coming along Drury-lane, there was a disturbance, and I missed the young man; I thought I could meet with him by the Docks or Blackwall, and, crossing Tower-hill, the policeman stopped me; he says I was out of breath, but it was a severe cold I had.</p>
               <p>
